{"author":{"id":"f270607f232f5ea3e06daa2368d41de7674a6d0d64158946f2581dde2c4881fc"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1605865623,"nonce":"zUFG8yEQBePcSFNTqiZchYF838U=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDczMTA2MzI1Nw==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/3313#issuecomment-731063257"},"message":"I know only very little about using multiqc on the command line, but what I understand is that it scans a directory for tool outputs it recognizes, then produces a report based on these.\nSo, in principle, the wrapper could just let multiqc do its job, and if a user, unintentionally, feeds the wrong input to the tool, they would get a report for that. However, the wrapper also customizes the reports based on the user's claim of what the input is and if the input was passed through to multiqc unchecked, then these customizations and the actual report wouldn't fit together.\nSo I believe this isn't really anything that typically affects multiqc command line users, but we need to get the Galaxy-specific checks right (unless we would want to do a major rewrite of the wrapper).","files":null}]}